c,l,a,r,i,t,y){c[a]=c[a]||function(){(c[a].q=c[a].q||[]).push(arguments)};t=l.createElement(r);t.async=1;t.src='https://www.clarity.ms/tag/'+i;y=l.getElementsByTagName(r)[0];y.parentNode.insertBefore(t,y);})(window, document, 'clarity', 'script', 'gzk1ekbi1n');</script></head><body vocab="http://schema.org/"><header><nav class="site"><div><span property="isPartOf" typeof="WebSite" resource="https://games.porg.es/"><a class="brand" property="url" href="https://games.porg.es/"><span property="name">Ways to Play</span></a></span><ul class="under-brand"><li><a href="/articles/">Articles</a></li><li><a href="/games/">Games</a></li></ul></div><form id=2search-box" role="search" method="get" action="https://duckduckgo.com/" target="_top"><span class="simple"><input type="search" name="q" required placeholder="Search this site" aria-label="Search this site"><button type="submit">рҹ”ҚпёҺ</button></span><input type="hidden" name="sites" value="games.porg.es"></form></nav></header><main><article property="mainEntity" typeof="http://schema.org/Article"><link property="copyrightHolder author publisher" href="#me"><h1 class="page-title" property="headline"><span class="simple" property="name">Tic-Tac-Toe</span></h1><p class="last-updated">Last updated: <time property="dateModified" datetime="2025-11-20">Thursday, 20 November 2025</time>.</p><p><span class="aka">Tic-Tac-Toe</span> is a simple game for two players that is well-known to result in a draw if played вҖҳrationallyвҖҷ. Unlike most board games, pieces cannot be moved or removed once placed, making it an ideal game to play with pen &amp; paper.</p><figure class="" property="image" typeof="ImageObject cc:Work"><dialog class="lightbox" id="lb-71bad30832fe52ca9d0ace7f4498599e"><img src="/img/6d9e10c48e74785e8e246af1adfdb9eb1121ce97.jpg" srcset="/img/6d9e10c48e74785e8e246af1adfdb9eb1121ce97-300.jpg 300w, /img/6d9e10c48e74785e8e246af1adfdb9eb1121ce97-600.jpg 600w, /img/6d9e10c48e74785e8e246af1adfdb9eb1121ce97-800.jpg 800w, /img/6d9e10c48e74785e8e246af1adfdb9eb1121ce97.jpg 1024w" sizes="(max-width: 300px) 300px, (max-width: 600px) 600px, (max-width: 800px) 800px, 1024px" width="1024" height="686" loading="lazy" alt="Several games of tic-tac-toe scrawled on a concrete wall."><div class="lightbox-under"><p></p><form method="dialog"><a href="/img/6d9e10c48e74785e8e246af1adfdb9eb1121ce97.jpg" role="button" target="_blank">Full Size (1024 Г— 686 pixels)</a><button class="lightbox-close">Close</button></form></div></dialog><a property="" href="#lb-71bad30832fe52ca9d0ace7f4498599e"><img class="figure-img" property="contentUrl" src="/img/6d9e10c48e74785e8e246af1adfdb9eb1121ce97-600.jpg" alt="Several games of tic-tac-toe scrawled on a concrete wall." width="1024" height="686" srcset="/img/6d9e10c48e74785e8e246af1adfdb9eb1121ce97-300.jpg 300w, /img/6d9e10c48e74785e8e246af1adfdb9eb1121ce97-600.jpg 600w, /img/6d9e10c48e74785e8e246af1adfdb9eb1121ce97-800.jpg 800w, /img/6d9e10c48e74785e8e246af1adfdb9eb1121ce97.jpg 1024w" sizes="(max-width: 575.98px) 300px, 600px"></a><figcaption><div property="caption"><p>Some tic-tac-toe games.</p></div><p><span property="copyrightNotice">В© <span property="copyrightYear">2012</span> <a property="cc:attributionURL" href="https://www.flickr.com/photos/65029995@N05/7429845046"><span property="copyrightHolder creator" typeof="Person"><span property="name">gerogeri </span></span></a>, <a property="license cc:license" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/2.0/" title="Licensed under the Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial-NoDerivatives license 2.0">рҹ…ӯрҹ…Ҝрҹ„ҸвҠң</a></span></p></figcaption></figure><section><h2>History</h2><p>The origins of tic-tac-toe are unclear. Many sources claim that it dates from antiquity, but the evidence to me suggests a more recent invention. Possibly it appeared as a degenerate version of Three MenвҖҷs Morris. Written references to the game only appear in the 19th century, and the game is particularly well-suited to being played with chalk on slatesвҖүвҖ”вҖүstandard equipment for schoolchildren during this period. Indeed, <span class="citation inline" id="cite-1"><a href="#ref-BerkshirePhrases"><cite>A Glossary of Berkshire Words and Phrases</cite></a> (<a href="https://archive.org/details/aglossaryberksh00lowsgoog/page/164">164</a>)</span> describes it as вҖңthe first game taught to children when they can use a slate pencilвҖқ.</p><figure class="aside" property="image" typeof="ImageObject cc:Work"><dialog class="lightbox" id="lb-ad761f40d2b353fa87bb56fc55d4a571"><img src="/img/d393fe018b3c16c4031c91efa92ab3c68f9bec6f.svg" width="800" height="800" loading="lazy" alt=""><div class="lightbox-under"><p></p><form method="dialog"><a href="/img/d393fe018b3c16c4031c91efa92ab3c68f9bec6f.svg" role="button" target="_blank">Full Size (800 Г— 800 pixels)</a><button class="lightbox-close">Close</button></form></div></dialog><a property="" href="#lb-ad761f40d2b353fa87bb56fc55d4a571"><img class="figure-img border-0" property="contentUrl" src="/img/d393fe018b3c16c4031c91efa92ab3c68f9bec6f.svg" alt="" width="800" height="800"></a><figcaption><div property="caption"><p>The small merels board with diagonals.</p></div><p><span property="copyrightNotice">В© <span property="copyrightHolder creator" typeof="Person" resource="#me"><span property="name"><span property="givenName">George</span> <span property="familyName">Pollard</span></span></span>, <a property="license cc:license" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/4.0/" title="Licensed under the Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial-ShareAlike license 4.0">рҹ…ӯрҹ…Ҝрҹ„Ҹрҹ„Һ</a></span></p></figcaption></figure><p>However, there is an early antecedent: a game equivalent in play, if not in presentation. <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alfonso_X_of_Castile">Alfonso X of CastileвҖҷs</a> <cite>Book of Games</cite><sup class="citation" id="cite-2"><a class="index" href="#ref-AlfonsoGames">B</a></sup>, published in 1283, includes the game <span lang="es">alquerque de tres</span> which is played on a small merels board with diagonals. Each player has three pawns which they place on the board one at a timerget="_blank">Full Size (3003 Г— 2000 pixels)</a><button class="lightbox-close">Close</button></form></div></dialog><a property="" href="#lb-d5ca279d8f175e5898150ead14ec4901"><img class="figure-img" property="contentUrl" src="/img/2e0c74a25b4718b180b9911c7dfd5993c41e6142-800.jpg" alt="A wall with a completed tic-tac-toe game drawn on it in chalk." width="3003" height="2000" srcset="/img/2e0c74a25b4718b180b9911c7dfd5993c41e6142-300.jpg 300w, /img/2e0c74a25b4718b180b9911c7dfd5993c41e6142-600.jpg 600w, /img/2e0c74a25b4718b180b9911c7dfd5993c41e6142-800.jpg 800w, /img/2e0c74a25b4718b180b9911c7dfd5993c41e6142-1200.jpg 1200w, /img/2e0c74a25b4718b180b9911c7dfd5993c41e6142.jpg 3003w" sizes="(max-width: 575.98px) 300px, (max-width: 991.98px) 600px, 800px"></a><figcaption><div property="caption"><p>A tic-tac-toe game on a wall in Marseille, France.</p></div><p><span property="copyrightNotice">В© <a property="cc:attributionURL" href="https://www.flickr.com/photos/nnova/5072574617/"><span property="copyrightHolder creator" typeof="Person"><span property="name"><span property="givenName">Nicolas</span> <span property="familyName">Nova</span></span></span></a>, <a property="license cc:license" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/2.0/" title="Licensed under the Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial license 2.0">рҹ…ӯрҹ…Ҝрҹ„Ҹ</a></span></p></figcaption></figure><section><h3>Other languages</h3><p>In Greek it is called <span lang="el" class="aka">П„ПҒОҜО»О№О¶Оұ</span> (<span lang="el-Latn">triliza</span>), or <span lang="el" class="aka">ПҖОұП„О·П„ПҢ</span> (<span lang="el-Latn">patito</span>) in Thessaloniki.<span class="footnote-indicator"></span><span class="footnote" role="note">This is given in <span class="citation inline" idcaption"><p>Tic-tac-toe games on a wall in the Medina of Fez (<span lang="ar">ЩҒШ§Ші Ш§Щ„ШЁШ§Щ„ЩҠ</span>), Morocco.</p></div><p><span property="copyrightNotice">В© <a property="cc:attributionURL" href="https://www.flickr.com/photos/henrykkcheung/8576897675/in/photostream/"><span property="copyrightHolder creator" typeof="Person"><span property="name">henrykkcheung </span></span></a>, <a property="license cc:license" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/2.0/" title="Licensed under the Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial-NoDerivatives license 2.0">рҹ…ӯрҹ…Ҝрҹ„ҸвҠң</a></span></p></figcaption></figure></section></section><section><h2>Automatic Players</h2><p>Being a simple game with a finite game tree, Tic-Tac-Toe is both easily programmed and ideal for early automation experiments, and so became one of the first games to be played by machines. As noted above, Charles Babbagemp" typeof="Person foaf:Person"><meta property="name foaf:name" content="Elwyn Berlekamp"><a property="sameAs" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elwyn_Berlekamp"><bdi><span property="familyName foaf:familyName">Berlekamp</span></bdi>, <bdi><span property="givenName foaf:givenName">Elwyn</span></bdi></a></span>, <span class="noun" property="author dcterms:creator" resource="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Horton_Conway" typeof="Person foaf:Person"><meta property="name foaf:name" content="Joh studied the problem but never built an actual machine.</p><p>The earliest fully automated player was constructed by a Frank T. Freeland of Philadelphia, who described its implementation in an 1879 journal article.<sup class="citation" id="cite-35"><a class="index" href="#ref-AutomaticTTT">AC</a></sup> According to the article, the machine was built and exhibited in 1878 before being moved to the University of Pennsylvania. Its whereabouts (if it still exists) are currently unknown.<span class="footnote-indicator"></span><span class="footnote" role="note">For more about Freeland, see <span class="citation inline" id="cite-36"><a class="indnts of <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/B._F._Skinner">B. F. Skinner</a>, the behavioural psychologist.<sup class="citation" id="cite-41"><a class="index" href="#ref-TheMouseWhoReinforced">AI</a>вҖҜ(73)</sup> In reality, the game is riggedвҖ”the chicken only ever pushes a single button, and the move to be played is chosen by a computer.<sup class="citation" id="cite-42"><a class="index" href="#ref-BirdBrainManual">AJ</a></sup></p><figure class="" property="image" typeof="ImageObject cc:Work"><dialog class="lightbox" id="lb-0bb901d559845491b7bee55514ed479e"><img src="/img/096b5320121e2b5873f7035b39e94645770dcc4b-1200.jpg" srcset="/img/096b5320121e2b5873f7035b39e94645770dcc4b-300.jpg 300w, /img/096b5320121e2b5873f7035b39e94645770dcc4b-600.jpg 600w, /img/096b5320121e2b5873f7035b39e94645770dcc4b-800.jpg 800w, /img/096b5320121e2b5873f7035b39e94645770dcc4b-1200.jpg 1200w, /img/096b5320121e2b5873f7035b39e94645770dcc4b.jpg 1203w" sizes="(max-width: 300px) 300px, (max-width: 600px) 600px, (max-width: 800px) 800px, (max-width: 1200px) 1200px, 1203px" width="1203" height="1239" loading="lazy" alt=""><div class="lightbox-under"><p></p><form method="dialog"><a href="/img/096b5320121e2b5873f7035b39e94645770dcc4b.jpg" role="button" target="_blank">Full Size (1203 Г— 1239 pixels)</a><button class="lightbox-close">Close</button></form></div></dialog><a property="" href="#lb-0bb901d559845491b7bee55514ed479e"><img class="figure-img" property="contentUrl" src="/img/096b5320121e2b5873f7035b39e94645770dcc4b-600.jpg" alt="" width="1203" height="1239" srcset="/img/096b5320121e2b5873f7035b39e94645770dcc4b-300.jpg 300w, /img/096b5320121e2b5873f7035b39e94645770dcc4b-600.jpg 600w, /img/096b5320121e2b5873f7035b39e94645770dcc4b-800.jpg 800w, /img/096b5320121e2b5873f7035b39e94645770dcc4b-1200.jpg 1200w, /img/096b5320121e2b5873f7035b39e94645770dcc4b.jpg 1203w" sizes="(max-width: 575.98px) 300px, 600px"></a><figcaption><div property="caption"><p>A surviving copy of Animal Behaviour EnterprisesвҖҷ Bird Brain game.</p></div><p><span property="copyrightNotice">В© <span property="copyrightYear">2004</span> <a property="cc:attributionURL" href="http://n2t.net/ark:/65665/ng49ca746ab-6f36-704b-e053-15f76fa0b4fa"><span property="copyrightHolder" typeof="Organization"><span property="name">Smithsonian</span></span></a>, under US fair use</span></p></figcaption></figure></section><section><h2>See also</h2><p>Some general references for the game are <span class="citation inline" id="cite-43"><a href="#ref-OxfordBG"><cite>The Oxford History of Board Games</cite></a> (112вҖ“3)</span>, <span class="citation inline" id="cite-44"><a href="#ref-Bell"><cite>Board and Table Games from Many Civilizations</cite></a> (vol. 1, p. 91)</span>, and <span class="citation inline" id="cite-45"><a href="#ref-Murray2"><cite>A History of Board-Games Other Than Chess</cite></a> (В§3.2.1, p. 40)</span>.</p><p>Gardner has further discussion on variants in <span cl=ss="citation inline" id="cite-46"><a href="#ref-WheelsLife"><cite>Wheels, Life, and Other Mathematical Amusements</cite></a> (94вҖ“105)</span>.</p></section><h2 id="references">References</h2><ol class="reference-list" type="A"><li><p id="ref-BerkshirePhrases" property="citation" typeof="Book bibo:Book fabio:Book"><span class="noun" property="author dcterms:creator" typeof="Person foaf:Person"><meta property="name foaf:name" content="Barzillai Lowsley"><bdi><span property="familyName foaf:familyName">Lowsley</span></bdi>, <bdi><span property="givenName foaf:givenName">Barzillai</span></bdi></span> (<time property="datePublished dcterms:issued" datetime="1888"><span property="fabio:hasPublicationYear">1888</span></time>). <a property="url" href="https://archive.org/details/aglossaryberksh00lowsgoog"><cite property="name">A Glossary of Berkshire Words and Phrases</cite></a>. <span property="publisher dcterms:publisher" typeof="Organization foaf:Organization" resource="#BerkshirePhrases-publisher"><span class="noun foaf:name" property="name">English Dialect Society</span>: <span class="noun" property="location">London, UK</span>. </span></p></li><li><p id="ref-AlfonsoGames" property="citation" typeof="Book bibo:Book fabio:Book"><span property="author" typeof="Organization"><span class="noun" property="name">Alfonso X</span></span> (<time property="datePublished dcterms:issued" datetime="1283"><span property="fabio:hasPublicationYear">1283</span></time>). <cite property="name">Libro de aГ§edrex, dados e tablas</cite>. <span property="publisher dcterms:publisher" typeof="Organization foaf:Organization" resource="#AlfonsoGames-publisher"><span class="noun foaf:name" property="name">Alfonso X</span>: <span class="noun" property="location">Toledo, Spain</span>. </span></p></li><li><aside class="reference-note footnote"><a href="https://archive.org/details/historyofboardga0000murr_p4b9">1978 reprint available here</a></aside><p id="ref-Murray2" property="citation" resource="urn:isbn:0198274017" typeof="Book bibo:Book fabio:Book"><span class="noun" property="author dcterms:creator" resource="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/H._J._R._Murray" typeof="Person foaf:Person"><meta property="name foaf:name" content="H. J. R. Murray"><a property="sameAs" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/H._J._R._Murray"><bdi><span property="familyName foaf:faspan></bdi>, <bdi><span property="givenName foaf:givenName">Cosmo</span></bdi></span> (<time property="datePublished dcterms:issued" datetime="1884"><span property="fabio:hasPublicationYear">1884</span></time>). вҖҳ<a property="url" href="https://archive.org/details/magazineofart07unse"><span class="noun" property="name headline">Some pictures of Children</span></a>вҖҷ. <span typeof="Periodical bibo:Journal fabio:Journal" resource="#MagazineOfArt-periodical"><link property="publisher␀␀␀publisher" href="#MagazineOfArt-publisher"><cite property="name">The Magazine of Art</cite></span> <span typeof="PublicationVolume bibo:CollectedDocument fabio:JournalVolume" property="isPartOf frbr:partOf